How you talk to AWS.

Every interaction with AWS goes through the same control plane. There are just three doors into it, and underneath, they all do the same thing.

The first door is the AWS Management Console, a web interface in your browser. It's best for learning a new service and for one-off exploration. The second is the AWS command line interface, or C-L-I, which runs commands from your terminal. It's best for scripting, automation glue, and ad-hoc operations. The third is the S-D-Ks, the software development kits, like boto-three for Python. These give you programmatic access from your own code, and they're best for application logic, infrastructure-as-code, and repeatable workflows.

Underneath all three are signed H-T-T-P-S requests to a regional A-P-I endpoint. The console is a web app calling those endpoints. The C-L-I is a thin wrapper over them. And the S-D-K is a typed wrapper in your programming language. A good habit is to learn a service in the console first, then move to the C-L-I or an S-D-K once you want it scripted and repeatable.
